sec.p:
It is recommended to continue the research into optimal configuration and operation of these hybrid renewable–fossil energy systems by:


pursuing optimal system efficiency through a configuration in which the SE is directly coupled to the air handler of the SH system or alternatively to the heat storage of an LTH system, and the solar heat capture is maximized by low heat storage temperatures that match the temperature requirements of the SH system;

improving the overall control strategy by implementing seasonably adjusted heat storage temperatures to increase solar heat capture and reduce standby losses;

further optimization of the solar panel configuration (in series, in parallel, mixed) with optimized variable glycol flow rate;

optimizing the heat storage to provide ample storage capacity for solar heat, allowing long SE operating cycles, without excessive heat losses to the environment;

investigating a more optimal placement of the various heat exchangers in the heat storage tank(s);

using a SE micro-cogeneration system with improved performance (comparable to or better than that of the auxiliary heat devices);

expanding the simulation model to produce DHW with a constant outlet temperature;

evaluating the influence of mandatory legionella sterilization cycles on the system performance; and

including an economic analysis of the Base Case and the various system configurations.
